TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Dynamic Inventory Problem with Unknown Demand Distribution
AU  - Iglehart, Donald L.
Y1  - 1964/04/01
PY  - 1964
DA  - 1964/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.10.3.429
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.10.3.429
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 429
EP  - 440
VL  - 10
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper we consider the dynamic inventory problem in which the demand distribution possesses a density belonging to either the exponential or range family of densities and having an unknown parameter. An a priori density is chosen for the unknown parameter. Using a Bayesian estimation scheme, inequalities are obtained for the optimal purchase policies as the amount of demand information varies. In addition, asymptotic expansions for the optimal policies are found as the number of observations of the demand becomes large. This paper extends the results of Scarf, [8].
AB  - In this paper we consider the dynamic inventory problem in which the demand distribution possesses a density belonging to either the exponential or range family of densities and having an unknown parameter. An a priori density is chosen for the unknown parameter. Using a Bayesian estimation scheme, inequalities are obtained for the optimal purchase policies as the amount of demand information varies. In addition, asymptotic expansions for the optimal policies are found as the number of observations of the demand becomes large. This paper extends the results of Scarf, [8].
